        <section class="sec-1">
            <h3><strong>PARC:Repetition</strong></h3>
            <p>Rhetoricrevealed</p>
            <a href="https://rhetoricrevealed.wordpress.com/about/">https://rhetoricrevealed.wordpress.com/about/</a>
            <img class="contrast" src="image/rhetoricrevealed.wordpress.com_about_.png" alt="Image-of-Rhetoricrevealed">
            <p>
                <b>Repetition</b>, which tells us that elements like color, text and graphic patterns should be repeated
                throughout our
                design and other designs with similar purposes. And finally, contrast, which tells us that we should
                create
                definitive differences between objects on the page that aren't similar to each other.
            </p>
        </section>
        <section class="sec-2">
            <h3><b>PARC: Alignment</b></h3>
            <p><b>merriam-webster</b></p>
            <a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/alignment">www.merriam-webster.com</a>
            <img class="space" src="image/www.merriam-webster.com_dictionary_alignment.png" alt="merriam-webster">
            <p>
                Exactly, what is PARC? Well, PARC is an acronym for four terms that we will use to create better and
                more
                efficient designs. The P stands for proximity, the A for alignment, R for repetition, and C for
                contrast.
            </p>
        </section>
        <section class="sec-3">
            <h3><b>Visual Hierarchy</b></h3>
            <p><b>merriam-webster</b></p>
            <a href="https://www.interaction-design.org/literature/topics/visual-hierarchy#:~:text=Visual%20hierarchy%20is%20the%20principle,guide%20them%20to%20desired%20actions.">www.interaction-design.org</a>
            <img class="visual" src="image/www.interaction-design.org_literature_topics_visual-hierarchy.png"
                alt="Visual-Hierarchy">
            <p>
                Visual hierarchy is the principle of arranging elements to show their order of importance. Designers
                structure
                visual characteristics—e.g., menu icons—so users can understand information easily. By laying out
                elements
                logically and strategically, designers influence users' perceptions and guide them to desired actions.
            </p>
        </section>
